force as well and more NGOs
than the United States.

00:31:48.832 --> 00:31:50.540
CAROL HILLS: I want
to talk about stress.

00:31:50.540 --> 00:31:52.760
It's a big topic in
your book, and it's

00:31:52.760 --> 00:31:56.860
a real concern for people in
the field of global health

00:31:56.860 --> 00:32:00.170
and a concern of Dean Williams
and the School of Public Health

00:32:00.170 --> 00:32:01.850
here.

00:32:01.850 --> 00:32:04.220
You talk about ways
to reduce stress--

00:32:04.220 --> 00:32:06.420
getting out of overdrive,
connecting with nature,

00:32:06.420 --> 00:32:09.260
making time for yourself,
confiding in a friend.

00:32:09.260 --> 00:32:11.720
And you talk, as you did
in your opening remarks,

00:32:11.720 --> 00:32:14.560
about how lifelong stress can--

00:32:14.560 --> 00:32:16.910
or managing lifelong
stress can really

00:32:16.910 --> 00:32:20.570
reduce the incidence
of chronic disease.

00:32:20.570 --> 00:32:21.730
But how do we--

00:32:21.730 --> 00:32:24.590
are there examples either
in the United States

00:32:24.590 --> 00:32:27.770
or overseas of
other places where

00:32:27.770 --> 00:32:31.160
it's, again, outside of
the realm of the individual

00:32:31.160 --> 00:32:34.040
who's learning and
taking responsibility?

00:32:34.040 --> 00:32:36.920
Are there health
care systems that

00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:40.280
are addressing stress
and reducing stress

00:32:40.280 --> 00:32:44.960
as a primary concern that
maybe the US could look to?

00:32:44.960 --> 00:32:48.080
DEEPAK CHOPRA: There are no
health care systems officially

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:52.040
in the world that are looking at
stress, which is the number one

00:32:52.040 --> 00:32:56.180
epidemic of our civilization,
which is directly

00:32:56.180 --> 00:32:59.750
or indirectly connected to
almost every chronic illness,

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:02.210
even risk for acute illness.

00:33:02.210 --> 00:33:03.410
So there are no programs.

00:33:03.410 --> 00:33:07.100
But there are many
volunteer organizations.

00:33:07.100 --> 00:33:09.770
I'll mention one
because I'm close to it.

00:33:09.770 --> 00:33:13.550
The Urban Yogis in
Queens, in New York,

00:33:13.550 --> 00:33:16.100
they've done a
remarkable job not only

00:33:16.100 --> 00:33:18.680
of improving their
well-being in a very

00:33:18.680 --> 00:33:21.800
impoverished
African-American community,

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:23.930
but they've become
leaders in their field.

00:33:23.930 --> 00:33:26.550
They're now teaching
this to other people,

00:33:26.550 --> 00:33:28.130
and the crime rate
is coming down.

00:33:28.130 --> 00:33:32.030
There's a direct correlation
between social violence

00:33:32.030 --> 00:33:34.107
and individual stress as well.

00:33:34.107 --> 00:33:35.940
CAROL HILLS: But crime
rates are coming down

00:33:35.940 --> 00:33:37.490
for a lot of other reasons too.

00:33:37.490 --> 00:33:38.150
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Say that again.

00:33:38.150 --> 00:33:39.170
CAROL HILLS: Crime
rates are coming down

00:33:39.170 --> 00:33:40.160
for a lot of other reasons too.

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:42.050
DEEPAK CHOPRA: In this
particular demographic

00:33:42.050 --> 00:33:44.110
we're looking at,
we're attributing it

00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:50.060
to the self-organization
of the community itself

00:33:50.060 --> 00:33:51.357
in this particular community.

00:33:51.357 --> 00:33:52.940
CAROL HILLS: One
thing I wanted to ask

00:33:52.940 --> 00:33:56.260
is it seems like in
the '60s and '70s

00:33:56.260 --> 00:33:59.140
in its various parts of,
certainly, American history,

00:33:59.140 --> 00:34:01.190
there were group
political movements,

00:34:01.190 --> 00:34:05.270
and it was the group that was
moving toward political ends

00:34:05.270 --> 00:34:07.190
and political ideals.

00:34:07.190 --> 00:34:09.739
And for the past 20
or 30 years, it's

00:34:09.739 --> 00:34:12.620
really been about kind
of self-realization,

00:34:12.620 --> 00:34:14.929
taking charge of one's self--
whether it's working out,

00:34:14.929 --> 00:34:17.330
whether it's fitness,
whether it's mindfulness.

00:34:17.330 --> 00:34:22.130
And is there a role for
politics and sort of group

00:34:22.130 --> 00:34:24.800
behavior in trying to achieve
these things since they

00:34:24.800 --> 00:34:28.699
are so critical for the
health of individuals

00:34:28.699 --> 00:34:30.339
for their entire life?

00:34:30.339 --> 00:34:32.690
DEEPAK CHOPRA: So I
started my career in Boston

00:34:32.690 --> 00:34:35.429
in the early '70s.

00:34:35.429 --> 00:34:36.679
And there was busing.

00:34:36.679 --> 00:34:39.170
There were racial
riots in Boston.

00:34:39.170 --> 00:34:42.210
You probably remember them too.

00:34:42.210 --> 00:34:47.520
There were a lot of issues
right then that were emerging.

00:34:47.520 --> 00:34:50.520
Feminism-- Gloria
Steinem was marching

00:34:50.520 --> 00:34:52.310
the streets of Cambridge.

00:34:52.310 --> 00:34:53.949
There was the peace movement.

00:34:53.949 --> 00:34:56.880
There was the green movement.

00:34:56.880 --> 00:34:58.560
And in my naive day--

00:34:58.560 --> 00:34:59.880
I was 24 years old--

00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:03.190
I thought we were going to
change the world in the next 10

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:03.690
years.

00:35:03.690 --> 00:35:06.020
And look where we've
gone now, we've

00:35:06.020 --> 00:35:09.040
regressed by 60
years I would say.

00:35:09.040 --> 00:35:12.780
So we are, right now,
not in a position

00:35:12.780 --> 00:35:16.680
where we can say that this
is the ideal situation

00:35:16.680 --> 00:35:20.850
for a society or a community
or a nation or the world.

00:35:20.850 --> 00:35:25.880
And we need to revive
that kind of zeitgeist

00:35:25.880 --> 00:35:30.120
where politics
ultimately will be

00:35:30.120 --> 00:35:35.100
influenced by social
opinion or public opinion,

00:35:35.100 --> 00:35:36.480
as it is always.

00:35:36.480 --> 00:35:39.030
You see right now
is what is happening

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:41.970
in the political world.

00:35:41.970 --> 00:35:46.440
It's being influenced
by social opinion.

00:35:46.440 --> 00:35:48.750
And I think in
order for well-being

00:35:48.750 --> 00:35:51.360
to be part of the
political arena,

00:35:51.360 --> 00:35:56.130
it's young people who
should now be both voting

00:35:56.130 --> 00:36:01.554
and getting involved in the
issues we're talking about.

00:36:01.554 --> 00:36:03.720
CAROL HILLS: I'm going to
introduce another question

00:36:03.720 --> 00:36:08.010
from someone who sent it in
in advance, Archana Basu.

00:36:08.010 --> 00:36:11.280
She asks, how can current
systems of health in the US

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:14.710
move to a more
preventative model of care?

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:16.710
DEEPAK CHOPRA: I think
current systems in the US

00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:18.930
have to listen to
what is happening

00:36:18.930 --> 00:36:20.700
in schools or public health.

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:23.310
Schools of public
health need to get

00:36:23.310 --> 00:36:25.680
better funding, which is
not happening at the moment,

00:36:25.680 --> 00:36:26.620
by the way.

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:29.070
Even though everyone's
aware that public health is

00:36:29.070 --> 00:36:34.270
the number one issue both for
prevention and for prediction

00:36:34.270 --> 00:36:37.950
of what happens in a society,
the funding is not happening.

00:36:37.950 --> 00:36:42.450
So we need a political
movement in that direction that

00:36:42.450 --> 00:36:46.920
can only come from the public.

00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:50.430
And I think we have an
advantage in the fact

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:52.980
that we can use
social media as well

00:36:52.980 --> 00:36:57.180
to bring these ideas to
everybody's attention.

00:36:57.180 --> 00:36:59.370
The internet, if
you look at it, it's

00:36:59.370 --> 00:37:01.830
the global brain right now.

00:37:01.830 --> 00:37:04.200
And it's a very
active global brain.

00:37:04.200 --> 00:37:07.050
You can send somebody a
tweet in South Africa,

00:37:07.050 --> 00:37:10.820
and you can give
them a dopamine hit.

00:37:10.820 --> 00:37:13.210
Or you can be abusive
on the internet

00:37:13.210 --> 00:37:15.070
and raise their blood pressure.

00:37:15.070 --> 00:37:19.150
So we are all connected.

00:37:19.150 --> 00:37:25.620
We are inseparably woven into
the fabric of being and living.

00:37:25.620 --> 00:37:27.780
We are monitoring
each other's brains.

00:37:27.780 --> 00:37:30.360
We are being monitored
by each other.

00:37:30.360 --> 00:37:32.760
And we are regulating
each other and being

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:34.670
regulated by each other.

00:37:34.670 --> 00:37:37.320
There's no such thing
as a separate self.

00:37:37.320 --> 00:37:40.740
So even self-realization
and all these movements

00:37:40.740 --> 00:37:45.486
that started with it's all
about me ultimately leads to we.

00:37:45.486 --> 00:37:47.550
CAROL HILLS: The me
leads to we, but it also

00:37:47.550 --> 00:37:49.120
leads to a lot of stress.

00:37:49.120 --> 00:37:52.050
I mean, the digital age is--

00:37:52.050 --> 00:37:55.650
online life is also
a big distraction.

00:37:55.650 --> 00:37:59.769
And so how do we
kind of counter that?

00:37:59.769 --> 00:38:01.560
People are really never
away from work now.

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:02.310
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Two
things-- one is technology

00:38:02.310 --> 00:38:04.350
is not going to go away.

00:38:04.350 --> 00:38:06.840
So if you don't like
what's happening

00:38:06.840 --> 00:38:12.270
in the world of technology
and social media

00:38:12.270 --> 00:38:16.170
and you don't adapt,
then Darwinian principles

00:38:16.170 --> 00:38:18.855
say that you will
become irrelevant.

00:38:18.855 --> 00:38:20.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:20.050 --> 00:38:24.750
So you cannot stop that
technology movement.

00:38:24.750 --> 00:38:25.950
How do we use it?

00:38:25.950 --> 00:38:27.855
Right now, it's being
used by trolls--

00:38:27.855 --> 00:38:28.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:28.640 --> 00:38:36.540
--AND by gangsters posing as
political leaders globally.

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:40.300
We need to get involved
in using social media,

00:38:40.300 --> 00:38:44.940
SO we can actually bring
awareness about these issues--

00:38:44.940 --> 00:38:49.140
violence, social justice,
economic justice, peace,

00:38:49.140 --> 00:38:52.060
conflict resolution,
climate change.

00:38:52.060 --> 00:38:55.350
This is the best
use of social media.

00:38:55.350 --> 00:38:58.020
And I use social media,
rarely prolifically,

00:38:58.020 --> 00:38:59.770
but I have times when I use it.

00:38:59.770 --> 00:39:05.100
So I have media time, exercise
time, meditation time,

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:06.340
and work time.

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:10.500
And I do one thing at a
time, because multitasking,

00:39:10.500 --> 00:39:11.550
your brain can't do it.

00:39:11.550 --> 00:39:13.080
It's a myth.

00:39:13.080 --> 00:39:15.730
Your cortical brain
cannot multitask.

00:39:15.730 --> 00:39:19.080
Only your reptilian
brain, which is

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:22.320
taking care of your
autonomic nervous system,

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:25.640
it's already multitasking
anyway without your help.

00:39:25.640 --> 00:39:30.900
But your conscious choices
have to be made mindfully.

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:34.560
And if you're multitasking, if
you're looking at your phone

00:39:34.560 --> 00:39:38.330
and speaking to me at the same
time, you're doing neither.

00:39:38.330 --> 00:39:39.660
So it's a myth.

00:39:39.660 --> 00:39:41.850
And it's the one
thing that actually

00:39:41.850 --> 00:39:45.490
ruins your neural
networks, because they

00:39:45.490 --> 00:39:48.880
get confused if you try
to do too many things

00:39:48.880 --> 00:39:50.230
all at the same time.

00:39:50.230 --> 00:39:54.780
That's the bane of media
and being seduced by it.

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:56.230
Technology is neutral.

00:39:56.230 --> 00:39:58.880
Are you going to use it
for destructive purposes?

00:39:58.880 --> 00:40:02.060
Or can you help
create a better world?

00:40:02.060 --> 00:40:05.440
CAROL HILLS: I think you and I
and many people in this room,

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:07.900
we have the luxury,
if we're willing,

00:40:07.900 --> 00:40:11.770
to compartmentalize and create
separate spaces for our life.

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:15.220
But again, putting it into
a public health context,

00:40:15.220 --> 00:40:18.010
are there other
examples or models

00:40:18.010 --> 00:40:21.010
where these kinds of things are
really being taken seriously,

00:40:21.010 --> 00:40:22.750
even at a very micro-level?

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:24.520
DEEPAK CHOPRA: In
the United States,

00:40:24.520 --> 00:40:26.590
everything becomes political.

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:30.860
So if you want to introduce
something to a school system,

00:40:30.860 --> 00:40:32.050
it becomes political.

00:40:32.050 --> 00:40:34.360
So it's a huge problem.

00:40:34.360 --> 00:40:39.520
But the best use of
knowledge is education.

00:40:39.520 --> 00:40:44.110
And education is easily
accomplished in schools,

00:40:44.110 --> 00:40:48.200
and education for
well-being should

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:51.650
be the most important
aspect of education.

00:40:51.650 --> 00:40:57.470
The word education, the word
comes from [? "educor" ?] which

00:40:57.470 --> 00:41:01.280
means to bring out what's
already at the core of a child

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:05.052
or a human being, which
is infinite creativity.

00:41:05.052 --> 00:41:06.010
And we're not doing it.

00:41:06.010 --> 00:41:09.650
We're giving them information
overload, which right now,

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:11.870
who needs that
with the internet?

00:41:11.870 --> 00:41:14.000
We can look up anything.

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:17.390
So it has to be-- public
health and education have

00:41:17.390 --> 00:41:18.890
to go together.

00:41:18.890 --> 00:41:22.351
In many parts of the
world, education is free.

00:41:22.351 --> 00:41:23.850
CAROL HILLS: And
are there any parts

00:41:23.850 --> 00:41:28.260
of the world where that
kind of thinking is going on

00:41:28.260 --> 00:41:29.510
DEEPAK CHOPRA: To some extent.

00:41:29.510 --> 00:41:32.750
In India, it is
happening to some extent.

00:41:32.750 --> 00:41:37.430
It's happening in
urban societies

00:41:37.430 --> 00:41:43.061
in New York and other
cities, but not enough.

00:41:43.061 --> 00:41:45.560
CAROL HILLS: We have another
question we received in advance

00:41:45.560 --> 00:41:48.320
from Marie Andre Lopez-Gomez.

00:41:48.320 --> 00:41:51.440
She asked, what is the
role of work in well-being,

00:41:51.440 --> 00:41:54.770
and how is the work culture in
the US affecting well-being?

00:41:54.770 --> 00:41:56.750
And she adds, are
there any examples

00:41:56.750 --> 00:42:00.440
of work cultures around the
world that offer examples?

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:04.400
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Well, here's the
unfortunately depressing data.

00:42:07.430 --> 00:42:10.460
Only 20% of people
in the United States

00:42:10.460 --> 00:42:12.560
are fully engaged
in their work, which

00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:16.400
means they enjoy
going to work, they

00:42:16.400 --> 00:42:19.910
enjoy working with
the people at work,

00:42:19.910 --> 00:42:23.870
they are complementing
and being complemented

00:42:23.870 --> 00:42:27.140
in their strengths,
they have shared vision,

00:42:27.140 --> 00:42:29.810
and they are
emotionally connected--

00:42:29.810 --> 00:42:32.090
only 20%.

00:42:32.090 --> 00:42:35.090
80% of people in the
American workforce

00:42:35.090 --> 00:42:38.180
are either disengaged
or actively disengaged.

00:42:38.180 --> 00:42:40.340
So disengaged means you
just go because it's

00:42:40.340 --> 00:42:41.900
a job you have to do.

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:45.460
Actively disengaged means
that you are unhappy,

00:42:45.460 --> 00:42:47.570
and you go to work to
make other people unhappy.

00:42:47.570 --> 00:42:50.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:57.040
This costs the United States
about $300 billion a year,

00:42:57.040 --> 00:42:59.540
job disengagement.

00:42:59.540 --> 00:43:03.230
Unfortunately, this is true
all over the world, by the way.

00:43:03.230 --> 00:43:06.320
There are some countries
where they're ahead

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:07.430
of the United States.

00:43:07.430 --> 00:43:10.440
If you look at overall
well-being in the buckets

00:43:10.440 --> 00:43:13.380
I mentioned-- work well-being,
social well-being, community

00:43:13.380 --> 00:43:16.024
well-being, the United States
is about 14th in the world.

00:43:16.024 --> 00:43:17.940
CAROL HILLS: What are
the countries that are--

00:43:17.940 --> 00:43:19.280
seem to be doing a bit better?

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:23.577
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Denmark,
Canada, even Panama.

00:43:23.577 --> 00:43:24.410
CAROL HILLS: Panama?

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:25.020
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Panama.

00:43:25.020 --> 00:43:26.220
CAROL HILLS: What
are they doing there?

00:43:26.220 --> 00:43:27.594
DEEPAK CHOPRA:
Well, I think it's

00:43:27.594 --> 00:43:30.020
a burgeoning economy
right now, and so they're

00:43:30.020 --> 00:43:31.890
doing very well right now.

00:43:31.890 --> 00:43:34.650
But there are other
countries Costa Rica,

00:43:34.650 --> 00:43:36.740
other Scandinavian countries.

00:43:36.740 --> 00:43:38.870
Of course, if you bring
up the Scandinavian model

00:43:38.870 --> 00:43:38.990
and these countries--

00:43:38.990 --> 00:43:41.115
CAROL HILLS: They're always
doing everything right.

00:43:41.115 --> 00:43:44.116
DEEPAK CHOPRA: --it becomes
a political issue again.

00:43:44.116 --> 00:43:45.454
[CHUCKLING]

00:43:48.510 --> 00:43:51.080
CAROL HILLS: Your
book, The Healing Self,

00:43:51.080 --> 00:43:53.270
which I read-- and I'm
actually taking some steps

00:43:53.270 --> 00:43:56.380
and trying to reduce the
clutter in my own mind.

00:43:56.380 --> 00:43:59.360
But your book, this
one and others,

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:01.490
they put a lot of
responsibility on individuals

00:44:01.490 --> 00:44:02.990
to take charge of
their health care,

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:05.870
to be an informed,
inquisitive patient.

00:44:05.870 --> 00:44:09.560
You have checklists,
things people can do.

00:44:09.560 --> 00:44:14.180
In the public health
sector, should we

00:44:14.180 --> 00:44:16.790
be thinking about
it differently?

00:44:16.790 --> 00:44:19.010
Is the individual
approach and the burden

00:44:19.010 --> 00:44:21.650
of the individual to make
things happen and take

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:23.859
charge, is that the right
approach in a public health

00:44:23.859 --> 00:44:24.358
setting?

00:44:24.358 --> 00:44:25.610
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Not completely.

00:44:25.610 --> 00:44:27.980
But of course, there can
not be social well-being

00:44:27.980 --> 00:44:30.110
in the absence of
personal well-being.

00:44:30.110 --> 00:44:32.210
That's a given.

00:44:32.210 --> 00:44:37.080
But when you have social
engagement around anything,

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:43.080
whether it's losing weight,
or providing a service,

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:48.900
or exercise, or
mindfulness practices,

00:44:48.900 --> 00:44:51.510
then the more socially
engaged you can get

00:44:51.510 --> 00:44:57.010
and the more you can do
participation in a group,

00:44:57.010 --> 00:45:00.640
the more likely you
are to be successful.

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:04.860
Now having said, that I've
created something which

00:45:04.860 --> 00:45:07.100
I call the internet
of well-being,

00:45:07.100 --> 00:45:11.940
where I bring together
experts in all these areas

00:45:11.940 --> 00:45:15.720
we mentioned, including
conflict resolution,

00:45:15.720 --> 00:45:18.480
personal relationship
management.

00:45:18.480 --> 00:45:21.960
It's free, and you get
people to participate,

00:45:21.960 --> 00:45:24.540
create their own
groups, and, ultimately,

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:27.480
create a blockchain movement--
which we haven't done,

00:45:27.480 --> 00:45:29.420
but we're in the process--

00:45:29.420 --> 00:45:33.420
so that there's a system
where people are rewarded even

00:45:33.420 --> 00:45:36.780
for little nudges,
standing up every hour

00:45:36.780 --> 00:45:42.690
or making sure that you get
10,000 steps a day or getting

00:45:42.690 --> 00:45:43.590
sleep.

00:45:43.590 --> 00:45:48.510
If we can participate as a group
and create a reward system,

00:45:48.510 --> 00:45:49.140
it works.

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:53.940
CAROL HILLS: You've had a
long and storied career,

00:45:53.940 --> 00:45:56.510
and you've become your
own brand, really.

00:45:56.510 --> 00:45:58.860
You're this huge figure
in the wellness movement.

00:45:58.860 --> 00:46:02.835
And there's other people,
Andrew Weil and Dr. Oz,

00:46:02.835 --> 00:46:04.210
there's lots of
people out there.

00:46:04.210 --> 00:46:06.600
And do you ever
feel like there's

00:46:06.600 --> 00:46:09.320
something paradoxical
about that,

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:13.200
of being sort of a brand name
in this field of wellness

00:46:13.200 --> 00:46:14.240
and mindfulness?

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:15.342
You know what I mean.

00:46:15.342 --> 00:46:16.800
DEEPAK CHOPRA:
Well, fortunately, I

00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:19.050
have a wife and kids who
don't take me seriously.

00:46:19.050 --> 00:46:21.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:21.870 --> 00:46:22.770
That helps a lot.

00:46:22.770 --> 00:46:24.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:24.750 --> 00:46:27.990
Secondly, I've
learned over the years

00:46:27.990 --> 00:46:31.680
not to believe in
my public persona.

00:46:31.680 --> 00:46:36.420
Because for everything that's
said about you that's good,

00:46:36.420 --> 00:46:38.220
somebody's saying
something about you

00:46:38.220 --> 00:46:40.350
that's the extreme opposite.

00:46:40.350 --> 00:46:45.420
So as you grow older, you learn
to handle it in a better way.

00:46:45.420 --> 00:46:47.700
And it wasn't planned.

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:50.604
I was planning to be
an internist and--

00:46:50.604 --> 00:46:52.020
CAROL HILLS: Right
here in Boston.

00:46:52.020 --> 00:46:53.520
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Right
here in Boston.

00:46:53.520 --> 00:46:54.570
And that's what I did.

00:46:54.570 --> 00:46:58.860
But then, I couldn't help notice
that I had two patients who

00:46:58.860 --> 00:47:02.190
had the same illness,
received the same treatment,

00:47:02.190 --> 00:47:05.220
saw the same doctor, and had
completely different outcomes.

00:47:05.220 --> 00:47:06.540
This person died.

00:47:06.540 --> 00:47:08.760
This person
recovered completely.

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:11.400
So I knew there was
something missing

00:47:11.400 --> 00:47:16.680
in our mechanistic
approach to our well-being

00:47:16.680 --> 00:47:20.100
or even looking at our
biological organism.

00:47:20.100 --> 00:47:22.440
We were looking at our
biological organisms

00:47:22.440 --> 00:47:25.420
as a physical
machine, and it's not.

00:47:25.420 --> 00:47:29.000
You can interfere with
mechanisms of disease,

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:32.710
but if you don't address
the origins of disease,

00:47:32.710 --> 00:47:37.330
no amount of mechanistic
interference is going to help.

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:41.700
So it was my journey, which
was accidental-- neuroscience,

00:47:41.700 --> 00:47:45.600
endocrinology, neuropeptides,
mind-body medicine,

00:47:45.600 --> 00:47:49.110
integrative well-being, and
now trying to figure out,

00:47:49.110 --> 00:47:51.100
what is it all about?

00:47:51.100 --> 00:47:53.100
CAROL HILLS: We're going
to turn to Q&amp;A in about

00:47:53.100 --> 00:47:55.450
a minute from online questions.

00:47:55.450 --> 00:47:58.740
But my last question to you
is, what is the research

00:47:58.740 --> 00:48:01.560
that either you're involved in
or other people are involved

00:48:01.560 --> 00:48:04.562
in that you're most excited
about in the field of wellness?

00:48:04.562 --> 00:48:06.270
DEEPAK CHOPRA: The
most exciting research

00:48:06.270 --> 00:48:10.470
is what I mentioned,
epigenetics,

00:48:10.470 --> 00:48:13.797
where you can see how
your genes are activated

00:48:13.797 --> 00:48:15.380
through every
experience, whether it's

00:48:15.380 --> 00:48:18.690
a perceptual experience
or a mental experience--

00:48:18.690 --> 00:48:20.130
so epigenetics.

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:25.380
The microbiome, looking at the
two million genes that you.

00:48:25.380 --> 00:48:27.780
You have only
25,000 human genes,

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:31.440
but you have two
million bacterial genes

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:35.490
that respond to every experience
but particularly to nutrition.

00:48:35.490 --> 00:48:38.160
So for me, that's very exciting.

00:48:38.160 --> 00:48:45.220
And the third is how we
can change and amplify

00:48:45.220 --> 00:48:48.880
the coordination between the
reptilian, emotional, and

00:48:48.880 --> 00:48:52.930
intellectual brain, which
is my work with Rudy Tanzi

00:48:52.930 --> 00:48:54.700
here at Harvard.

00:48:54.700 --> 00:48:59.030
Now that he and I have worked
so many years together,

00:48:59.030 --> 00:49:02.290
actually we are so aware of
what's happening in our brain,

00:49:02.290 --> 00:49:05.050
even in a conversation
like this,

00:49:05.050 --> 00:49:10.000
I know which part of my brain
I'm looking at right now.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.070
CAROL HILLS: We're going
to move to questions

00:49:12.070 --> 00:49:14.320
that have come in online.

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:18.760
And the first one
is from Emmanuel.

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:22.750
And she asks, what is the
single most threatening problem

00:49:22.750 --> 00:49:25.360
facing a child's health
and security today and

00:49:25.360 --> 00:49:26.470
in the near future?

00:49:26.470 --> 00:49:28.630
And how can we as
parents and a society

00:49:28.630 --> 00:49:31.390
equip our children to
avoid this problem?

00:49:31.390 --> 00:49:36.260
What can we do today to change
the course of their future.

00:49:36.260 --> 00:49:38.370
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Well,
unfortunately again,

00:49:38.370 --> 00:49:42.890
childhood trauma and
childhood abuse--

00:49:42.890 --> 00:49:45.440
whether it's sexual
abuse, physical abuse,

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:47.510
emotional abuse--

00:49:47.510 --> 00:49:51.000
all leads to problems
in adulthood.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:54.550
It sets also something
called the brain set point

00:49:54.550 --> 00:49:58.000
for happiness or unhappiness.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:02.370
If a child is given what I
call the Four As-- attention,

00:50:02.370 --> 00:50:08.290
deep listening; affection, deep
caring and love; appreciation,

00:50:08.290 --> 00:50:11.560
noticing the child's
strengths; and acceptance,

00:50:11.560 --> 00:50:15.820
not trying to conform their
behavior to how you think they

00:50:15.820 --> 00:50:20.260
should be, acceptance, and
looking at their strengths--

00:50:20.260 --> 00:50:24.460
that child will grow up
to be a healthy adult.

00:50:24.460 --> 00:50:30.580
And if a child is in some
way abused or ignored--

00:50:30.580 --> 00:50:35.110
ignored is even worse than,
by the way, being criticized.

00:50:35.110 --> 00:50:37.515
Because ignored means
you don't exist.

00:50:37.515 --> 00:50:40.370
And then, that child will g--

00:50:40.370 --> 00:50:44.740
become a dysfunctional
adult emotionally.

00:50:44.740 --> 00:50:49.420
May end up winning a
political election, though.

00:50:49.420 --> 00:50:53.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:53.640 --> 00:50:57.130
CAROL HILLS: Here's a
question from Wi Amin--

00:50:57.130 --> 00:50:59.590
that's the name that's given.

00:50:59.590 --> 00:51:02.774
How do you believe societal
taboos or norms contribute

00:51:02.774 --> 00:51:03.690
to health improvement?

00:51:03.690 --> 00:51:06.700
And how do they hinder
health improvement?

00:51:06.700 --> 00:51:09.100
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Well, when
societal taboos and norms

00:51:09.100 --> 00:51:15.920
become purveyors of
self-righteous morality,

00:51:15.920 --> 00:51:21.250
then they interfere
with creativity

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:25.390
and authentic behavior.

00:51:25.390 --> 00:51:28.390
Imposed morality never works.

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:32.200
So that's where
societal mores and norms

00:51:32.200 --> 00:51:37.960
and religious institutions can
cause problem and even abuse.

00:51:37.960 --> 00:51:42.070
But many religious institutions
and societal institutions

00:51:42.070 --> 00:51:45.070
actually do a lot for the world.

00:51:45.070 --> 00:51:48.490
Some of the biggest humanitarian
movements in the world

00:51:48.490 --> 00:51:51.340
are actually
religious movements,

00:51:51.340 --> 00:51:54.400
so we should give them credit
for the good that they do

00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:56.500
and the service they provide.

00:51:56.500 --> 00:51:58.300
They are the people
who are working

00:51:58.300 --> 00:52:00.280
in these impoverished areas.

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:02.080
CAROL HILLS: And also,
your own background

00:52:02.080 --> 00:52:05.050
and the Ayurvedic
traditions, in many ways,

00:52:05.050 --> 00:52:07.760
come from particularly Indian
cultures and traditions.

00:52:07.760 --> 00:52:08.593
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Yeah.

00:52:08.593 --> 00:52:10.960
It's very strong influenced
by the wisdom traditions

00:52:10.960 --> 00:52:13.870
of India, yes.

00:52:13.870 --> 00:52:16.330
CAROL HILLS: Here's a
question from Raphael.

00:52:16.330 --> 00:52:19.570
He asks, what are your thoughts
about cultural appropriation

00:52:19.570 --> 00:52:21.940
in reference to Western
medicine starting

00:52:21.940 --> 00:52:24.700
to adopt ideas of
mindfulness, meditation,

00:52:24.700 --> 00:52:26.922
and alternative medicine?

00:52:26.922 --> 00:52:28.630
DEEPAK CHOPRA: I think
it's a great thing

00:52:28.630 --> 00:52:29.640
if it helps the world.

00:52:32.890 --> 00:52:34.540
I look at the
future when I'm not

00:52:34.540 --> 00:52:38.650
around where nationalism
or extreme nationalism

00:52:38.650 --> 00:52:44.380
will be considered a tribal
disease, that as we move

00:52:44.380 --> 00:52:47.800
into the future, especially
with the next generation

00:52:47.800 --> 00:52:53.500
and the next generation,
we'll be global citizens.

00:52:53.500 --> 00:52:56.950
And we will adapt
to other cultures.

00:52:56.950 --> 00:53:00.580
I have a grandson
right now who is

00:53:00.580 --> 00:53:04.640
a little bit Chinese, a little
bit Indian, and, of course,

00:53:04.640 --> 00:53:06.820
he lives in America.

00:53:06.820 --> 00:53:11.260
He speaks Spanish, Hindi,
English, and Mandarin

00:53:11.260 --> 00:53:13.180
at the same time.

00:53:13.180 --> 00:53:15.054
That's the future
citizen of the world.

00:53:15.054 --> 00:53:16.720
CAROL HILLS: He's a
fully-realized self.

00:53:16.720 --> 00:53:18.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:18.830 --> 00:53:21.560
DEEPAK CHOPRA: That is
the future of the world.

00:53:21.560 --> 00:53:26.770
And so I think we need to go
beyond our tribal behavior.

00:53:26.770 --> 00:53:31.810
And I think extreme
nationalism is just tribalism.

00:53:31.810 --> 00:53:33.850
Cultural
appropriation-- cultures

00:53:33.850 --> 00:53:37.040
get richer when they
mix with each other.

00:53:37.040 --> 00:53:40.850
So I'm not one for
total cultural identity.

00:53:40.850 --> 00:53:42.720
Culture can be a baggage.

00:53:42.720 --> 00:53:47.055
It can also be access to
good food and to good music.

00:53:47.055 --> 00:53:48.000
[CHUCKLING]

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:53.070
But other than that, I think
we need a multicultural society

00:53:53.070 --> 00:53:54.430
and a multicultural world.

00:53:54.430 --> 00:53:57.190
And America is the
best example of that

00:53:57.190 --> 00:54:02.070
so far, unless we
go the other way now

00:54:02.070 --> 00:54:04.449
with our immigration policies.

00:54:04.449 --> 00:54:06.240
CAROL HILLS: Here's a
question from Fatima.

00:54:06.240 --> 00:54:09.060
In your role as a physician
and spiritual guru,

00:54:09.060 --> 00:54:11.220
could you please elaborate
on the interaction

00:54:11.220 --> 00:54:15.070
between mental state
and physical health?

00:54:15.070 --> 00:54:17.850
DEEPAK CHOPRA: You can't
separate mental state

00:54:17.850 --> 00:54:19.320
and physical health.

00:54:19.320 --> 00:54:24.160
Wherever the mind goes,
the molecules follow.

00:54:24.160 --> 00:54:26.560
In fact, they're inseparable.

00:54:26.560 --> 00:54:29.310
So this distinction
between mind--

00:54:29.310 --> 00:54:34.290
mental state and physical
state is artificial.

00:54:34.290 --> 00:54:37.290
I can give you bad news,
and your blood pressure

00:54:37.290 --> 00:54:42.630
will go up in a moment if it
affects you, that bad news.

00:54:42.630 --> 00:54:45.810
On the other hand, if
you're feeling appreciated,

00:54:45.810 --> 00:54:50.340
wanted, and loved, you'll
have a different biochemistry.

00:54:50.340 --> 00:54:53.550
Your state of mind
even influences the way

00:54:53.550 --> 00:54:55.860
your food is metabolized.

00:54:55.860 --> 00:54:58.920
So because the
different chemistries

00:54:58.920 --> 00:55:02.460
in the body when you're
stressed or when you're relaxed

00:55:02.460 --> 00:55:04.530
or when you're celebrating--

00:55:04.530 --> 00:55:06.710
completely different.

00:55:06.710 --> 00:55:09.990
So there's no distinction
between mind and body.

00:55:09.990 --> 00:55:12.000
We should use one
word, body-mind,

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:15.810
just the way we use
wave-particle, mass-energy,

00:55:15.810 --> 00:55:17.130
space-time--

00:55:17.130 --> 00:55:19.300
body-mind.

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:21.750
CAROL HILLS: Here's a
question from Deborah J.

00:55:21.750 --> 00:55:25.110
As a public health professional,
what actionable steps

00:55:25.110 --> 00:55:28.350
can we take to encourage
better holistic and self-care

00:55:28.350 --> 00:55:30.370
for our patients?

00:55:30.370 --> 00:55:33.600
DEEPAK CHOPRA: I think
every physician in the field

00:55:33.600 --> 00:55:36.520
should be an educator as well.

00:55:36.520 --> 00:55:39.360
So when I was in
practice in Boston,

00:55:39.360 --> 00:55:41.580
I used to give my
patients a choice.

00:55:41.580 --> 00:55:44.980
I would tell them, I'm happy
to give you a tranquilizer,

00:55:44.980 --> 00:55:46.350
a sleeping pill--

00:55:46.350 --> 00:55:48.250
in those days, an antacid.

00:55:48.250 --> 00:55:51.120
We didn't have these
sophisticated H2 receptor

00:55:51.120 --> 00:55:54.920
blockers or proton
pump inhibitors.

00:55:54.920 --> 00:55:59.820
But I realized very quickly
that 90% of all prescriptions

00:55:59.820 --> 00:56:05.670
were for five things-- pain,
anxiety, nausea, insomnia,

00:56:05.670 --> 00:56:07.990
and constipation.

00:56:07.990 --> 00:56:10.710
If you want to remember
the acronym, it's PANIC.

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:12.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:12.750 --> 00:56:17.490
P-A-N-I-C. I used to watch
my nurses waking up patients

00:56:17.490 --> 00:56:19.020
to give them sleeping pills.

00:56:19.020 --> 00:56:20.977
Mr. Smith, will
you please wake up?

00:56:20.977 --> 00:56:22.560
I have to give you
your sleeping pill.

00:56:22.560 --> 00:56:24.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:24.150 --> 00:56:27.360
So all these things are
very easily manageable.

00:56:27.360 --> 00:56:29.010
So I would tell
my patients, I'll

00:56:29.010 --> 00:56:30.700
give you a prescription
if you want.

00:56:30.700 --> 00:56:33.260
But on Friday, I'm going to
give a lecture on well-being.

00:56:33.260 --> 00:56:34.500
Show up.

00:56:34.500 --> 00:56:36.300
And so then I noticed
that more people

00:56:36.300 --> 00:56:39.960
were showing up for the lecture
than for the prescription.

00:56:39.960 --> 00:56:43.290
And to physicians out
there in public health,

00:56:43.290 --> 00:56:45.340
you can even charge for it.

00:56:45.340 --> 00:56:47.400
Charge a little bit
for your lectures.

00:56:47.400 --> 00:56:49.840
They'll be valued.

00:56:49.840 --> 00:56:53.100
But make sure they're less
than a prescription in price.

00:56:55.860 --> 00:56:58.230
CAROL HILLS: Here's a
question from Adele.

00:56:58.230 --> 00:57:00.120
What research topics
would Dr. Chopra

00:57:00.120 --> 00:57:02.460
recommend for young
scholars to analyze

00:57:02.460 --> 00:57:06.060
on the interface between
well-being and spirituality?

00:57:06.060 --> 00:57:08.010
DEEPAK CHOPRA:
And spirituality--

00:57:08.010 --> 00:57:11.160
look up a paper called
"Nonduality and Well-Being"--

00:57:11.160 --> 00:57:12.700
"Nonduality and Well-Being."

00:57:12.700 --> 00:57:16.890
It's about the relationship of
spirituality and well-being.

00:57:16.890 --> 00:57:20.010
And basically, it
means that the more--

00:57:20.010 --> 00:57:21.630
you know, what is spirituality?

00:57:21.630 --> 00:57:23.340
It's just the
question I asked you.

00:57:23.340 --> 00:57:24.480
Are you aware?

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:27.810
The more self-aware you
are, that's spirituality.

00:57:27.810 --> 00:57:30.040
Don't mix it up with religion.

00:57:30.040 --> 00:57:35.880
The more aware you are of your
inner self, and the more aware

00:57:35.880 --> 00:57:41.850
you are of your mental activity
and your perceptual activity,

00:57:41.850 --> 00:57:45.030
and the more aware you
are of your choices,

00:57:45.030 --> 00:57:46.410
that improves your well-being.

00:57:46.410 --> 00:57:50.821
So spirituality is being
self-aware, period.

00:57:50.821 --> 00:57:53.070
CAROL HILLS: Here's a
question-- it's a long question,

00:57:53.070 --> 00:57:54.670
but you have to
give a short answer.

00:57:54.670 --> 00:57:56.086
Because we're
running out of time.

00:57:56.086 --> 00:57:56.634
Here it is.

00:57:56.634 --> 00:57:58.050
DEEPAK CHOPRA:
Time doesn't exist.

00:57:58.050 --> 00:57:59.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:59.980 --> 00:58:02.900
It's a human construct.

00:58:02.900 --> 00:58:05.960
No other animal knows
what time it is now.

00:58:05.960 --> 00:58:09.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:09.560 --> 00:58:11.120
CAROL HILLS: This is from Ida.

00:58:11.120 --> 00:58:12.810
And it's kind of a
serious question.

00:58:12.810 --> 00:58:15.660
Given the ever-increasing
language of hate, exclusion,

00:58:15.660 --> 00:58:18.360
and violence, and its impact
on the many who find themselves

00:58:18.360 --> 00:58:21.360
at the receiving end, how
can we limit the assaults

00:58:21.360 --> 00:58:24.770
and/or help improve wellness
caused by this kind of stress?

00:58:24.770 --> 00:58:29.100
DEEPAK CHOPRA: Yeah, by
the way, it's only obvious

00:58:29.100 --> 00:58:32.100
when you look at the internet,
because the dominant activity

00:58:32.100 --> 00:58:33.750
is that of trolls.

00:58:33.750 --> 00:58:36.840
But by and large, people
are actually out there

00:58:36.840 --> 00:58:40.440
to help each other, to
engage with each other.

00:58:40.440 --> 00:58:43.710
And understand that
relationship is who we are.

00:58:43.710 --> 00:58:46.410
